6. Longitudinal analysis

2023-06-20

Back to content page

Learning objective

  • Recognize and describe correlations between multiple measurements (Repeated/multiple/longitudinal measures)
  • Analyse longitudinal data using generalized estimating equations (GEE)
  • Perform model selection for variables and correlation structure for GEE

1 Longitudinal analysis

Background

  • Measurements made repeatedly over time for each subject
    • Data can be collected retrospectively or prospectively
    • Subjects usually assumed to be independent (too complicated if clustered sample over time); Within subjects are dependent/correlated
  • Another name: panel data for sociologists and economists
  • Benefits:
    • Provide stronger evidence on the causal effect (time element useful coz causes precedes outcome)
    • Allow observation of change in subjects (get time-dependent variables)
    • Higher power given the same number of subjects (more info in diff time point)
  • Cons:
    • More costly (need follow-up)

2 GEE model

GEE model

  • Marginal model response depends on the covariates only (i.e.do not model each level, but model diff levels at the same time and combine them tgt to directly model outcome and covariant)
  • It is an extension of GLM model for correlated or clustered data
    • It is based on quasi-likelihood but not exact likelihood, so model comparison use QIC instead of AIC
    • Need to specify model/link function/data type (e.g., linear or logistic regression)
    • Need to specify correlation matrix (specify how data is correlated) as nuisance parameter (parameter we r not interested in the value, but need to include in model to account for sth)
  • Assumptions
    1. Measurements are independent across subjects
    2. Measurements can dependent/correlated within subjects
    3. Correctly specify model (i.e.link function \(g(\mu_i) =x_i^{'}\beta\))

Correlation structure

  • Specify how the observations are correlated within subjects
    • 4 Commonly used working correlation structure: independence, exchangeable, AR(1), unstructured
    • The number of unknown parameters are different for diff structure and are estimated from data
      • e.g.AR(1): 1 unknown parameter
      • e.g.unstructured: 3 unknown parameters for 3 repeated measurements, (k^2-k)/2 =k(k-1)/2 in general

Characteristics of GEE model

  • The estimated parameters are efficient (i.e.smallest standard error (highest power)) if the correlation structure is correctly specified
  • The estimated parameters are still unbiased even with misspecification of the correlation structure
    • However, the standard error will be less accurate (need to increase sample size)
  • GEE use a robust estimator to do correction on standard error taking that fact that its correlated dataset (sandwich estimator, combine SE when its IID and SE when its correlated)
    • So even we assume independence correlation structure, we still get diff SE compared with GLM.
  • Interpretation of estimate depends on model used. (same as GLM)
  • Handling of missing data
    • Estimates are valid under MCAR
    • Model still able to give estimate without imputation, e.g., M1 and M2 without M3 can provide estimate if AR correlation

GLM model and residual correlation

## Fit a GLM model
glm.ohio <- glm(resp~age+smoke, family=binomial, data=ohio)
summary(glm.ohio)
#Age and maternal smoking are both significant at 5% sig. level (p-val = 0.036,0.028)

## Correlation of residuals from the fitted model
cor(glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-2],glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-1])
cor(glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-2],glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==0])
cor(glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-2],glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==1])

cor(glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-1],glm.ohio$residuals[ohio$age==-0])

GEE model (R)

  • Package: geepack
    • Obtain estimate geeglm(formula, family, corstr="independence", id, data, subset)
      • formula, family, data, subset same as glm()
      • corstrcorrelation structure, such as independence (by default), exchangeable, ar1, unstructure
      • ididentifies the cluster/subject where multiple measurements were made
    • Obtain CI
      • confint() doenst work for geeglm object
      • esitcon to estimate CI linear combination of coefficient (tho we usually only interested in 1 coefficient)
        • linear combination example 0,1,1 = 0beta0 + 0beta1 + 1*beta2 (obtain CI of age + smoke
  • Comparison between GLM and GEE
    • GLM ignored the dependence between observations, so it will
      • Overestimate SE of time dependent predictors
        GLM thinks between-subject variability was not accounted for GLM assume variability of time-dependent predictors to be randomness that needed to be accounted for, while GEE correctly attribute variation across time to repeated measure
      • Underestimate SE of time independent predictors
        GLM consider multiple measurements as additional independent samples Time independent variable from the same subject is the same in different time points. For example there are 500 subjects measured 4 times, GLM think its 2000 while GEE think its 500 observations => GLM underestimate SE.

Comparison of estimates 

## Fitting GEE model
gee.indp <- geeglm(resp~age+smoke, family=binomial, data=ohio, id=id, corstr = "independence") #Binomial for logistic regression; ID to specify from the same subject
summary(gee.indp)
#Age is still significant but not smoking status

## Obtain estimate and CI
require(doBy)
exp(c(esticon(gee.indp, c(0,0,1))$estimate,esticon(gee.indp,c(0,0,1))$lwr, esticon(gee.indp, c(0,0,1))$upr)) #exp coz its odds ratio; use c to combine as vector; lwr & upr to get lower and upper bound of CI
exp(c(esticon(gee.indp, c(0,1,0))$estimate,esticon(gee.indp,c(0,1,0))$lwr, esticon(gee.indp, c(0,1,0))$upr))
#On average, children with maternal smoking does not have a significantly different risk of wheezing. 
#On average, older children (between subjects) / children getting older (within subjects) will have a lower risk of wheezing
#Use "on average" coz GEE didn't estimate individual effect, just population effect

Model comparison (R)

  1. Compare nested models that differ by the inclusion or exclusion of one or more variables
    • Perform quasi-likelihood ratio test using anova()
  2. Fit GEE models with exchangeable, AR(1) and unstructured correlation structure and compare the results. Under package MESS:
    • Quasi-likelihood under the independence model information criterion (QIC) (not AIC coz quasi-likelihood)
    • Can also use correlation information criteriorn (CIC) (BIC before without likelihood)
    • Lower value indicates better model fit
    • Note: it can also be used to select variable
## 1 Nexted models differ in variables
gee.indp0 <- geeglm(resp ~ age, id=id, data=ohio, family=binomial, corstr="independence")
anova(gee.indp, gee.indp0) #model 1 = age+smoke; model 2 = age
## Analysis of 'Wald statistic' Table
## 
## Model 1 resp ~ age + smoke 
## Model 2 resp ~ age
##   Df   X2 P(>|Chi|)
## 1  1 2.34      0.13
#Maternal smoking is not significant (p-val = 0.13)

Missing data (R)

  • waves option in geeglm can specify the order of the observations
## Create missing dataset
set.seed(111)
n <- nrow(ohio)
n.missing <- 100 #no. of missing data
missing.x <- sample(1:n, n.missing, replace=F) #missing row
missing.y <- sample(c(3,4), n.missing, replace=T) #missing column (3,4 = age, smoke)

ohio.miss <- ohio
ohio.miss$waves = ohio.miss$age + 3 #Create a variable to specify the ordering of the repeated measures (dunno order if we miss age)
ohio.miss[cbind(missing.x, missing.y)] <- NA

## Fit GEE model in missing dataset
gee.ar1.miss <- geeglm(resp~age+smoke, family=binomial, waves=waves, data=na.omit(ohio.miss), id=id, corstr = "ar1") #na.omit to omit missing data
summary(gee.ar1.miss)
#Estimates becomes less significant (e.g. p-val for age change from 0.011 to 0.032)
## 
## Call:
## geeglm(formula = resp ~ age + smoke, family = binomial, data = na.omit(ohio.miss), 
##     id = id, waves = waves, corstr = "ar1")
## 
##  Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std.err   Wald Pr(>|W|)    
## (Intercept)   -1.890   0.117 263.24   <2e-16 ***
## age           -0.101   0.047   4.58    0.032 *  
## smoke          0.188   0.184   1.04    0.307

Model diagnostics

  • GEE is an estimating procedure not based on formal likelihood function
    • Standard likelihood-based goodness-of-fit statistics and model diagnostics not applicable
    • Residual plots for assessing the specified mean model
      In theory, we can compare model-expected mean and observations but it is still difficult so we wont touch too much on model diagnostics

GEE modelling strategy

  • Need to put correct variable in the model instead on focusing on correlation structure
    • Modelling of the mean structure most important
  • Correlation structure wont affect result too much, but we can still
    • Use a reasonable correlation structure
      • Can assume independence for the working correlation structure if the expected correlation among repeated measurements is weak
      • Always use the robust estimate for the standard error (i.e.use GEE instead of GLM)
    • Compare the estimates from different assumed correlation structure
    • Can test different correlation structure by QIC

3 GLMM model

  • Another approach to analyze longitudinal data
  • Fit the Ohio data using GLMM (in package lme4)
require(lme4)
ohio.glmm <- glmer(resp~age+smoke+(1|id), family=binomial,data=ohio) #consider id as "cluster/groups"
summary(ohio.glmm)

Review

  • GEE estimates the population-averaged effects for longitudinal data (vs individual for random effect model)
  • Correlations among repeated measurements as nuisance parameters
  • GEE is robust to mis-specification of the variance (or correlation structure)
  • Model selection can be done by QIC or quasi-likelihood ratio test
  • GLMM can also be used for longitudinal data, but the estimated effects have subject-specific interpretation

Real-life example

  • Effect of expanding medicaid for parents on childrens health insurance coverage lessons from the oregon experiment randomized trial by DeVoe et al. JAMA, Pediatr, 2015
    • Objective: to estimate the effect on a childs health insurance coverage status when (1) a parent randomly gains access to health insurance and (2) a parent obtains coverage
    • Subjects: 14,409 children in Oregon
    • Outcome: Oregon Health Program (OHP) coverage (assessed monthly) => Use GEE
  • Conclusions
    • Childrens odds of having OHP coverage increased when their parents were randomly selected to apply for Medicaid.
    • Children whose parents were selected and subsequently obtained coverage benefited most.

                  direction = "wide")
head(ohio.w)

## Changing from 'wide' form to 'long' form
ohio.l <- reshape(ohio.w, varying = list(c(3,5,7,9),c(4,6,8,10)), v.names = c("age","resp"), 
                  idvar="id", times=1:4, direction = "long") #list = columns corresponds to age and resp
ohio.l <- ohio.l[order(ohio.l$id, ohio.l$time),] #reorder by id and time

4 Practical (previous exam question)

A study recruited 100 heavy drinkers to participate in an educational program, who were then followed up every three months for 4 times. At each follow-up, the readiness to change (RTC) on alcohol behaviour was assessed through a questionnaire, which was then converted to a score. The number of heavy drinking days (HDD) in the past 30 days was also recorded. Data are stored in the file rtc.csv, which included:

data1 <- read.csv("Data/rtc.csv")

a) Overview of data

  1. Give a brief overview of the data including the sample size, age and sex distribution of the subjects, and the pattern of readiness to change score and heavy drinking days.
## sample size
length(unique(data1$id)) # N=100
data1.flat <- data1[!duplicated(data1$id),] #get 1 row for each individual
## age (continuous variable)
summary(data1.flat$age) #see min, max, mean etc
hist(data1.flat$age,las=1,xlab="Age",ylab="Number of cases",main=NA) #visualize distribution of age

## sex (discrete variable)
table(data1.flat$male) #count of sex
prop.table(table(data1.flat$male)) #prop of sex
## RTC and HDD (spagetti plot for repeated measure)
set.seed(1)
with(data1,interaction.plot(time,id,jitter(rtc),ylab='Readiness to change', legend=F,
                            lty=1, col=sample(1:20, max(id), replace=T),las=1))

library("ggplot2")
with(data1,interaction.plot(time,id,jitter(hdd),ylab='Heavy drinking days', legend=F,
                            lty=1, col=alpha("gray",0.6),las=1))

## 44 56

b) Fit GEE model

  1. Fit appropriate generalized estimating equation models (GEE) to assess the association between RTC and HDD, accounting for potential confounding effect of sex and age. It is expected that HDD at different follow-ups are correlated for the same person. Use at least two different correlation structures for your GEE model and select the best model (Should use log link/poisson family coz outcome is discrete).
gee.indp <- geeglm(hdd~age+male+rtc,data=data1,id=id,
                   family=poisson,corstr = "independence")
gee.exch <- geeglm(hdd~age+male+rtc,data=data1,id=id,
                   family=poisson,corstr = "exchangeable")

                  family=poisson,corstr = "ar1")
gee.unstr <- geeglm(hdd~age+male+rtc,data=data1,id=id,
                    family=poisson,corstr = "unstructured")
